diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's predominantly seen in children. The symptoms you've described are characteristic, especially when they appear in tandem.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease resulting from a group A streptococcus infection, known for causing a pink-red rash. It can present with fever and other symptoms as noted, though periungual desquamation typically occurs in the convalescent phase.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections, often associated with tampon use, but not exclusively. Symptoms can match, particularly the fever and desquamation.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's often a reaction to a medication or an infection. Fever, skin peeling (which could be interpreted as similar to desquamation), and conjunctivitis are key symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection transmitted by a tick. Symptoms include fever, rash (which can affect palms and soles, potentially linking to foot edema), and sometimes conjunctivitis.

diagnoses.name: Cellulitis
diagnoses.description: A common bacterial skin infection. It can cause redness, swelling, and warmth in the affected area (potentially linking to foot edema), and fever. Typically lacks the specific signs of conjunctivitis and desquamation but can present with a wide range of systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause the vessels in the skin, intestines, kidneys, and joints to start leaking. Symptoms may include rash, joint pain, abdominal pain, and kidney involvement but can present with fever and other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Gonococcal Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A rare complication of a gonorrhea infection, which can lead to fever, pus-filled lesions, and as a result, might show symptoms like pyuria. Skin and eye manifestations can occur, correlating with some of the symptoms described.

diagnoses.name: Acute Poststreptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease of the kidneys that can follow infection with certain strains of streptococcus bacteria. Symptoms include edema, often in the face or lower extremities, and can include hematuria which might be misidentified as pyuria without proper testing.

diagnoses.name: Leptospirosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial disease that affects humans and animals. It can lead to wide-ranging symptoms, including fever, conjunctivitis, and kidney damage, which might be suggested by pyuria. Edema and rash can also occur in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Hepatic Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: Chronic liver condition characterized by progressive scarring of liver tissue; can cause hyperactivity due to toxin buildup affecting the brain, with associated increases in certain immunoglobulin levels as a response to liver damage.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions where the immune system mistakenly attacks healthy body tissue, potentially leading to increased immunoglobulins, fibrosis in various organs, and gastrointestinal symptoms like vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder affecting the peripheral nervous system, potentially causing raised immunoglobulin levels and might indirectly lead to symptoms like blepharospasm due to nerve damage.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by dry eyes and mouth, which could lead to blepharospasm. It may also cause systemic effects such as hyperactivity due to CNS involvement, and fibrosis in various organs.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, leading to widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs including skin, joints, and potentially leading to fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Primary Biliary Cholangitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic disease that slowly destroys bile ducts in the liver, possibly leading to liver fibrosis, which can cause an increase in immunoglobulin M (IgM).

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, potentially causing vomiting and can lead to various systemic manifestations including hyperactivity.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Myeloma
diagnoses.description: A cancer of plasma cells which can lead to increased levels of immunoglobulins in the blood or urine, bone lesions, and potentially indirectly lead to symptoms like fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when donor bone marrow or stem cells attack the recipient. Can cause fibrosis of the organs, increased immunoglobulins, and various gastrointestinal symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Neurofibromatosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder causing tumors in the nervous system, which might lead to an array of symptoms including hyperactivity, and in some cases, fibrosis around the tumor sites.

diagnoses: Vitamin deficiency (e.g., Vitamin C deficiency leading to scurvy)

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones. Hypothyroidism may not cause noticeable symptoms in the early stages, but over time, untreated hypothyroidism can cause a number of health problems, such as obesity, joint pain, infertility, and heart disease.

diagnoses.name: Reactive Airway Disease
diagnoses.description: A term used to describe respiratory conditions characterized by wheezing, coughing, and shortness of breath. This term is often used when it's unclear whether asthma or another obstructive lung disease is the cause.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands. In people with sarcoidosis, abnormal masses or nodules called granulomas, consisting of inflamed tissues, form in certain organs of the body.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: Allergic rhinitis is inflammation of the inside of the nose caused by an allergen, such as pollen, dust, mould, or flakes of skin from certain animals. It's a very common condition, estimated to affect around 1 in every 5 people in the U.S.

diagnoses.name: Yellow Nail Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder characterized by nail changes, respiratory disorders, and lymphedema. The nails become thickened and yellowed, respiratory issues such as chronic cough and bronchiectasis develop, and swelling caused by excess lymph fluid in body tissues can occur.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Inflammation caused by lupus can affect many different body systems — including your joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A condition that affects a woman’s hormone levels, leading to various symptoms including irregular menstrual periods, excess hair growth, acne, and obesity. It's known that PCOS is related to hormonal imbalances that affect the ovaries and ovulation.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs. Symptoms include breathing difficulty, cough, mucus (sputum) production and wheezing. It's typically caused by long-term exposure to irritating gases or particulate matter, most often from cigarette smoke.

diagnoses.name: Urticaria
diagnoses.description: Also known as hives, urticaria is a skin reaction that causes itchy welts, which range in size. Chronic urticaria is when the condition lasts for more than six weeks and is often triggered by certain allergens.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An uncommon inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash. The condition can affect adults and children, and its signs and symptoms typically appear suddenly.

diagnoses: Secondary infections from scratching or environmental factors

diagnoses.name: Human Papillomavirus Infection
diagnoses.description: A common viral infection that can cause warts, including genital warts. It's possible for individuals with HPV to experience anxiety due to the diagnosis and related symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and produces an increased number of white cells, which could explain the basophilia. The diagnosis of such a condition can lead to anxiety and obsessive-compulsive behaviors as coping mechanisms.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic disorder in which a person has uncontrollable, reoccurring thoughts (obsessions) and behaviors (compulsions) that he or she feels the urge to repeat over and over.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition that disrupts the body's ability to defend itself against disease-causing agents, potentially leading to an increase in infections like warts due to HPV. Anxiety and obsessive-compulsive behavior can be secondary to the stress of managing a chronic illness.

diagnoses.name: Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.description: This condition can lead to osteopenia, as an overproduction of parathyroid hormone can result in too much calcium being extracted from the bones. Anxiety and mood changes are common symptoms related to calcium imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD)
diagnoses.description: PTSD can manifest in various psychological symptoms, including anxiety and obsessive-compulsive behaviors. Individuals with PTSD might also neglect their health, leading to conditions such as osteopenia from lack of physical activity or nutritional issues.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD)
diagnoses.description: An anxiety disorder characterized by chronic anxiety, exaggerated worry, and tension, even when there is little or nothing to provoke it. This can exacerbate or be comorbid with other disorders such as OCD.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus, if untreated, can progress to AIDS, weakening the immune system and increasing susceptibility to infections like HPV. Anxiety and obsessive-compulsive behaviors may also manifest in the individual's response to the disease.

diagnoses.name: Anemia of Chronic Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that can occur with chronic infections or diseases such as cancer. It can lead indirectly to basophilia and affect bone health, potentially contributing to osteopenia.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Hypothyroidism can contribute to mood disorders, including anxiety, and affect bone density, leading to osteopenia.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often presents with dry eyes and dry mouth, which could explain the dysgeusia and difficulty focusing vision due to dryness.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: Iron deficiency can sometimes cause dry eyes and difficulty focusing vision, along with oral manifestations that could be mistaken for leukoplakia.

diagnoses.name: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory condition that can cause leukoplakia-like lesions in the mouth. It can also cause dry mouth, potentially leading to dry eyes and dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: This deficiency can cause a wide range of neurological symptoms including hyperactivity, and oral symptoms that could resemble leukoplakia.

diagnoses.name: ATTENTION-DEFICIT/HYPERACTIVITY DISORDER (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: While primarily affecting attention and activity levels, associated conditions or treatments might lead to or exacerbate other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV infection can cause leukoplakia and has been associated with dry eyes. It can also indirectly cause other symptoms mentioned due to immune system damage.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: Diabetes can lead to dry eyes, and some oral manifestations might resemble leukoplakia. Poorly controlled diabetes might also lead to symptoms of dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can have ocular manifestations such as dry eyes and neurologic symptoms that might include difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: Hyperactivity is a common symptom, and it can also cause dry eyes. Furthermore, it might have an indirect role in various oral health issues.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It could cause severe eye symptoms, including dry eyes and vision issues, and oral symptoms like leukoplakia.

dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Myeloproliferative disorders (e.g., polycythemia vera, essential thrombocythemia)

diagnoses.name: Chronic Alcohol Use Disorder
diagnoses.description: Chronic and excessive consumption of alcohol, leading to liver damage, abnormal liver enzymes, mood lability, and easy bruising.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that causes inflammation and damage to the liver, leading to abnormal liver enzymes, easy bruising, and potentially mood changes.

diagnoses.name: Viral Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the liver caused by a virus, leading to symptoms like abnormal liver enzymes, mood lability, and easy bruising.

diagnoses.name: Non-alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition where fat builds up in the liver, causing abnormal liver enzymes, and can be associated with obesity and metabolic syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Cirrhosis
diagnoses.description: A late stage of scarring (fibrosis) of the liver caused by many forms of liver diseases and conditions, such as hepatitis and chronic alcoholism.

diagnoses.name: Primary Biliary Cholangitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic disease that destroys bile ducts in the liver, resulting in abnormal liver enzymes and easy bruising due to diminished liver function.

diagnoses.name: Wilson's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare inherited disorder that causes copper to accumulate in the liver, brain, and other vital organs, leading to abnormal liver enzymes and neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Hemochromatosis
diagnoses.description: An inherited condition in which the body absorbs too much iron from the diet, leading to abnormal liver enzymes, easy bruising, and liver damage.

diagnoses.name: Bacterial Vaginosis
diagnoses.description: A type of vaginal inflammation caused by the overgrowth of bacteria naturally found in the vagina, which can disrupt the natural balance of bacteria.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the cavities around nasal passages (sinuses) become inflamed and swollen for at least 12 weeks, despite treatment attempts.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Presence of chronic kidney disease can exacerbate other conditions, affect platelet count, and contribute to various cardiovascular diseases.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection
diagnoses.rationale: May be a direct contributor to the patient's clinical presentation, especially in the context of chronic kidney disease which predisposes the patient to infections.

diagnoses.name: Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy
diagnoses.rationale: Given as a symptom, it is a crucial diagnosis to manage due to its significant cardiovascular implications.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Thrombocytosis
diagnoses.rationale: Often seen in response to conditions such as chronic infection (e.g., chronic urinary tract infection), inflammation, or in the context of chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Might be inferred from 'glycemic lability', indicating fluctuations in blood sugar levels, which can exacerbate or be exacerbated by kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Acute Stress Reaction
diagnoses.rationale: Takotsubo cardiomyopathy is commonly triggered by acute emotional or physical stress.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive Heart Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Common in patients with chronic kidney disease and can contribute to the development of cardiomyopathies.

diagnoses.name: Sepsis
diagnoses.rationale: An underlying or complicating systemic response to infection, such as a urinary tract infection, which can be severe in patients with chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Heart Failure
diagnoses.rationale: A possible complication of takotsubo cardiomyopathy and chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.rationale: Common in chronic kidney disease patients due to reduced erythropoietin production and complications that may lead to bleeding (contributing to thrombocytosis if reactive).

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which there is a deficiency of red blood cells or hemoglobin in the blood, leading to fatigue, weakness, and shortness of breath. Anemia is common in chronic kidney disease due to decreased erythropoietin production.

diagnoses.name: Electrolyte Imbalance
diagnoses.description: Abnormal levels of electrolytes in the body, often occurring with chronic kidney disease. This can affect numerous body systems and may cause presyncope.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: A condition of elevated blood pressure, which is a common consequence of chronic kidney disease. This can exacerbate the risk of cardiovascular events.

diagnoses.name: Thyrotoxicosis
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from the excessive concentration of thyroid hormones, which can cause hyperthyroidism and lead to symptoms like presyncope.

diagnoses.name: Euthyroid Sick Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition where individuals with a critical illness, including those with severe cysts or chronic kidney disease, have abnormal findings on thyroid function tests but do not necessarily have intrinsic thyroid disease.

diagnoses.name: Ménière's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, tinnitus, and progressive hearing loss, it could be related to fluid disturbances such as those seen in hyperthyroidism.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Heart Failure
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition where the heart doesn't pump blood as well as it should. It can be exacerbated by conditions like hypertension, a common comorbidity of chronic kidney disease, and can lead to presyncope.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: An inherited disorder characterized by the growth of numerous cysts in the kidneys, which can cause chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Acute Otitis Media
diagnoses.description: An infection of the middle ear, primarily affecting children. It can be more prevalent or severe in cases of systemic illness or immune dysfunction, as might be seen with chronic kidney disease or hyperthyroidism.

diagnoses.name: Renal Osteodystrophy
diagnoses.description: A bone disorder that occurs when the kidneys fail to maintain the proper levels of calcium and phosphate in the blood, associated with chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, weakness, especially on one side of the body, confusion, trouble speaking, and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms include numbness or weakness in one or more limbs, partial or complete loss of vision, prolonged double vision, tingling or pain in parts of your body, and slurred speech.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a brief period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke, but usually lasting only a few minutes and causing no permanent damage. Common symptoms include weakness, paralysis, or numbness of the face, arm or leg, typically on one side of the body, slurred or garbled speech or difficulty understanding others, and blindness in one or both eyes or double vision.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraine with aura is a type of migraine that involves visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear about 10 to 60 minutes before the actual headache begins. Symptoms of the aura phase may include seeing flashing lights, blind spots, and tingling in one arm or leg.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Symptoms can vary greatly depending on the brain tumor's size, location and rate of growth and may include new onset or change in pattern of headaches, unexplained nausea or vomiting, vision problems, such as blurred vision, double vision or loss of peripheral vision, gradual loss of sensation or movement in an arm or a leg, difficulty with balance, speech difficulties, confusion in everyday matters, personality or behavior changes, seizures, especially in someone who doesn't have a history of seizures.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Symptoms may include temporary confusion, a staring spell, uncontrollable jerking movements of the arms and legs, lost consciousness or awareness, psychic symptoms such as fear, and numbness or tingling.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barre Syndrome is a rare disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body. In its most severe form Guillain-Barre syndrome is a medical emergency.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, ALS is a progressive nervous system disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, causing loss of muscle control. ALS often begins with muscle twitching and weakness in a limb, or slurred speech. Eventually, ALS affects control of the muscles needed to move, speak, eat and breathe.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: Lupus is a systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Inflammation caused by lupus can affect many different body systems, including your joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs. Symptoms include fatigue, joint pain, rash, and fever.

diagnoses.name: Conversion disorder (Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder)
diagnoses.description: Conversion disorder, also called Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder, is a condition in which you show psychological stress in physical ways. The disorder can present symptoms such as weakness, paralysis, or numbness in a limb or other parts of the body, speech issues, seizures, and abnormal gait, without a physical cause.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is often accompanied by visual disturbances (scintillation) and other sensory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms such as aphasia and vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain, which can cause symptoms like nausea, vomiting, and aphasia depending on its location.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV)
diagnoses.description: A disorder arising in the inner ear that causes short periods of dizziness or vertigo when the head is moved in certain positions.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves, potentially causing speech disturbances like aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a brief interruption of blood flow to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, which may cause symptoms mirroring a stroke.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from restricted blood flow to the back of the brain, causing symptoms like vertigo and scintillation.

diagnoses.name: Cerebral Aneurysm
diagnoses.description: A bulge in a blood vessel in the brain that can leak or rupture, causing severe headaches, nausea, vomiting, and blurred vision.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that leads to episodes of vertigo (spinning sensation), hearing loss, tinnitus (ringing in the ear), and a feeling of fullness in the ear. It often affects only one ear.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain or close to it. Symptoms can include seizures, nausea, vomiting, a headache that gets worse in the morning, weakness, or numbness in one part of the body, dizziness, and behavioral changes.

Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble seeing, walking, severe headache, dizziness, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, causing stroke-like symptoms but usually no lasting damage.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuronitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the vestibular nerve, a nerve in the ear that helps control balance. This can lead to vertigo, a severe spinning sensation, as well as nausea, vomiting, and difficulty focusing the eyes.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that may or may not cause a headache but does induce vertigo, dizziness, and balance issues. Patients may also experience nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to sound (phonophobia).

diagnoses.name: Labyrinthitis
diagnoses.description: An inner ear infection that can affect balance and hearing. Symptoms can include vertigo, dizziness, hearing loss, and a ringing sound in your ears.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. It affects nerves leading to your extremities. Symptoms can include pain, tingling, or numbness—loss of feeling—in the hands, arms, feet, and legs.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: Migraine is a neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound. Migraines can begin in childhood or may not occur until early adulthood.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to your brain. TIAs are often warning signs of a future stroke. Symptoms of a TIA are similar to that of a stroke but last only a few minutes and cause no permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barre Syndrome is a rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: Myasthenia gravis is characterized by weakness and rapid fatigue of any of the muscles under your voluntary control. It's caused by a breakdown in the normal communication between nerves and muscles. There's no cure for myasthenia gravis, but treatment can help relieve signs and symptoms, such as weakness of arm or leg muscles, double vision, drooping eyelids, and difficulties with speech, chewing, swallowing, and breathing.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Encephalitis is inflammation of the brain. There are several causes, but the most common is viral infection. Encephalitis can cause flu-like symptoms, such as a fever or severe headache, or more serious symptoms, such as confusion, seizures, or sensory changes.

diagnoses.name: Vertebral or Carotid Artery Dissection
diagnoses.description: A vertebral or carotid artery dissection is a tear in one of the arteries that carry blood to the brain. It can lead to a stroke. Symptoms may include headache, neck pain, vision problems, and weakness in one part of the body. These symptoms may mimic those of other neurological conditions.
